The '''Egyptian presidential election, 2011''', which will be held on September , 2011 <ref name="2011 ELECTORAL CALENDAR">[http://www.angelfire.com/ma/maxcrc/2011.html 2011 ELECTORAL CALENDAR]</ref><ref name="IFES Election Guide">[http://www.electionguide.org/country.php?ID=65 IFES Election Guide]</ref>, is the second allegedly contested presidential election in [[Egypt]]'s history. [[Hosni Mubarak]], the [[incumbent]] [[Rulers and heads of state of Egypt|President of Egypt]], may not run for this election which opens the door for many names to be suggested to take his place as President of Egypt. Some of those names are [[Mohamed ElBaradei]] ''(the ex-Director General of the [[International Atomic Energy Agency]] (IAEA), and the winner of the 2005 [[Nobel Peace Prize]])'', [[Amr Moussa]] ''(the current [[Secretary-General]] of the [[League of Arab States]], and former [[Egypt]]ian [[Foreign Minister]])'', [[Ahmed Zewail]] ''([[Egyptians|Egyptian]]-[[United States|American]] scientist, and the winner of the 1999 [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry]])'', [[Gamal Mubarak]] ''(the General Secretary of the Policy Committee of the [[National Democratic Party (Egypt)|National Democratic Party]] and the younger of the two sons of current [[Egypt]]ian President [[Hosni Mubarak]])'' among others.
